  <section class="section" id="about">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="about-split">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">How It Works</p>
          <h2>Understanding the schemes</h2>
          <p>The UK's Environment Act 2021 introduced mandatory requirements for new developments to offset their impact on local ecosystems. Two key mechanisms fund this recovery: Biodiversity Net Gain and Nutrient Neutrality.</p>

          <div class="scheme-box">
            <h4>Biodiversity Net Gain (BNG)</h4>
            <p>Mandatory for all new planning permissions in England since February 2024. Developers must demonstrate a minimum 10% improvement in biodiversity on and around their site, measured using the DEFRA Biodiversity Metric. Where on-site provision is insufficient, they must purchase "BNG units" from offsite habitat providers — typically landowners who restore or create habitats under a 30-year legal agreement.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="scheme-box">
            <h4>Nutrient Neutrality (NN)</h4>
            <p>Applies in catchments designated as nutrient-sensitive by Natural England — primarily areas draining to protected rivers and estuaries suffering from excess nitrogen or phosphorus. Before gaining planning permission, developers must prove their scheme will not worsen nutrient levels. They do this by purchasing nutrient credits from landowners who remove land from intensive agricultural use, reducing the nutrient load entering the water system.</p>
          </div>

          <p>Both schemes create a genuine, tradeable market: developers face a legal obligation to buy; landowners can supply. Westmoreland Biodiversity operates as an independent broker — ensuring both parties get fair value and that every transaction meets the regulatory standard.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">The Process</p>
          <h2>From first call to signed agreement</h2>
          <p>Our end-to-end process ensures nothing falls through the cracks. Here's what to expect when you work with us:</p>

          <div class="timeline">
            <div class="timeline-item">
              <h4>Initial Assessment</h4>
              <p>We review your land or development site and identify which schemes are applicable. This is free and without obligation.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="timeline-item">
              <h4>Ecological Survey &amp; Baseline</h4>
              <p>For BNG, we commission or review a DEFRA Metric baseline assessment. For NN, we calculate the nutrient budget using accepted Natural England methodology.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="timeline-item">
              <h4>Matching &amp; Negotiation</h4>
              <p>We match landowners with developers seeking credits in the same Local Planning Authority area or catchment. We negotiate pricing and terms transparently.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="timeline-item">
              <h4>Legal Agreement</h4>
              <p>All trades are secured through a Conservation Covenant or Section 106 agreement, providing long-term legal certainty for both parties and the Local Planning Authority.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="timeline-item">
              <h4>Monitoring &amp; Reporting</h4>
              <p>Landowners are supported with ongoing habitat management guidance and reporting obligations throughout the agreement term, ensuring payments continue uninterrupted.</p>
            </div>
          </div>


        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

