  <!-- ── FAQ ────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section section--alt" id="faq">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header centered">
        <p class="eyebrow">Frequently Asked Questions</p>
        <h2>Plain answers to common questions</h2>
        <p>If you don't find what you're looking for, get in touch — we're happy to help.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            <span>What types of land are suitable for BNG or nutrient credits?</span>
            <i class="faq-icon">+</i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Arable farmland, improved grassland, semi-natural grassland, scrub, woodland and wetland can all be suitable, depending on the scheme. The key factor for BNG is the potential to improve habitat condition — lower-quality land often has more "uplift" potential and can generate more units. For nutrient credits, land in nutrient-sensitive catchments that can be converted from intensive agriculture to low-input habitat is particularly valuable. We carry out a free eligibility check before you commit to anything.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            <span>Do I have to change how I farm my land?</span>
            <i class="faq-icon">+</i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>It depends on the scheme and which parcels are enrolled. For BNG, only the habitat enhancement areas are subject to management prescriptions — the rest of your farm continues as normal. For nutrient neutrality, the enrolled land must be converted away from intensive production (e.g. no synthetic fertilisers or cultivations), but this can work well for fields you're already considering entering into agri-environment schemes. Many landowners successfully stack these schemes alongside Countryside Stewardship.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            <span>How long do the agreements last?</span>
            <i class="faq-icon">+</i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>BNG habitat management agreements run for a minimum of 30 years, as required by the Environment Act 2021. Nutrient neutrality credits are typically structured over 80–125 years depending on the Local Planning Authority's requirements. These durations reflect the long-term nature of ecological recovery — but they also mean long-term, legally secured income for landowners. The agreements are registered as Conservation Covenants or Section 106 obligations and run with the land, so they transfer with any future sale.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            <span>How much could my land be worth?</span>
            <i class="faq-icon">+</i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Credit values vary significantly by location, habitat type and local developer demand. For BNG, low-distinctiveness arable land converted to a priority habitat can generate 20–40+ units per hectare. BNG unit prices currently range from £1,500 to £3,500+ per unit depending on the habitat type and location. For nutrient credits, prices depend on the nutrient-sensitive catchment and demand — prices have ranged from £5,000 to £20,000+ per credit in active catchments. The only way to get an accurate figure is a site-specific assessment, which we provide free of charge.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            <span>Are there planning implications for enrolling my land?</span>
            <i class="faq-icon">+</i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Habitat enhancement for BNG and land management changes for nutrient credits do not typically require planning permission themselves — they are agricultural land management activities. However, the conservation covenant or S106 agreement is recorded as a legal charge on the title, which will appear in any conveyancing search. We recommend landowners inform their mortgage provider and take independent legal advice before signing any agreement. We can recommend solicitors experienced in this area.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            <span>What does Westmoreland Biodiversity charge?</span>
            <i class="faq-icon">+</i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>We work on a brokerage fee basis, charged as a percentage of the transaction value when an agreement completes. There are no upfront fees for landowners or developers. The initial assessment, land eligibility review and matching conversations are entirely free. Our fee structure is clearly explained before you commit to anything, and we are always transparent about how we earn. We do not charge both sides — our fee is agreed with you upfront.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            <span>I'm a developer — how quickly can you find credits?</span>
            <i class="faq-icon">+</i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Timescales depend on the catchment and the volume required. In areas where we have established landowner relationships, we can often provide indicative credit availability within a few days and move to a heads of terms agreement within 2–4 weeks. For larger or more unusual requirements, allow 4–8 weeks. In all cases, we aim to provide you with a written confirmation of credit availability as quickly as possible so it can be included in your planning application. Contact us early — the sooner we begin, the smoother the process.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            <span>Are you regulated, and how do I know the credits are valid?</span>
            <i class="faq-icon">+</i>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>All BNG credits we broker are assessed using the mandatory DEFRA Biodiversity Metric and all transactions are secured through Conservation Covenants registered with the Secretary of State or Section 106 agreements with Local Planning Authorities — both legally binding and enforceable instruments. Nutrient credit calculations follow Natural England's published methodology and are accepted by Local Planning Authorities in designated catchments. We provide full documentation packages to developers for planning submission. We are happy to discuss our due diligence processes in detail.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

